  "chunk_index": 32,
  "summary": "Detective Hakast presents several clocks to Mrs. Melina Rivallion during the investigation. Mrs. Rivallion expresses interest in a gilded clock and reiterates that her husband, Harry Castleton, maintained the appearance of a respectable, upper-class gentleman, which is how she originally fell in love with him. When questioned about the name \"Rosemary,\" she recalls a redhead named Rosalie but cannot confirm a connection to her husband. She also observes that one clock's hands are pointing to 4:13. Mrs. Rivallion agrees to provide identification for a trial in two days, noting that she married Castleton over twenty years ago at St. Michael's Church in Dunbrooke.\n\nAfter her departure, Detective Inspector Gray arrives, and Hercule Poirot observes that Castleton’s respectable appearance was likely his modus operandi. Poirot suspects that multiple women may be seeking revenge against him and specifically ponders a clock inscribed with the name \"Rosemary.\"\n\nLater, Colin Lamb meets with Poirot, who expresses annoyance regarding renovations in his apartment building. They discuss the identification of the deceased in the Crocetta trial as Harry Castleton, noting that Mrs. Rivallion has been cooperative. The conversation shifts to the death of a girl named Ina, who died in a phone booth on Wilbraham Crescent; Poirot critiques Lamb's failure to gather specific details regarding her movements and the location of a grille where her heel became stuck. The following evening, Lamb meets with Hakast, who reveals that Harry Castleton made a living by marrying or engaging wealthy, gullible women to gain control of their savings before disappearing.",
